<race_condition_advanced_guide>
<title>ADVANCED RACE CONDITIONS</title>

<critical>Advanced race condition exploitation focuses on TOCTOU attacks, limit-overrun, double-spending, single-packet attacks, and database transaction races. Modern applications with distributed architectures are particularly vulnerable.</critical>

<scope>
- Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) exploits
- Limit-overrun attacks (rate limits, quotas, inventory)
- Double-spending patterns in payment and credit systems
- Single-packet attack techniques for tight synchronization
- Database transaction race conditions
- Distributed system races (microservices, event-driven architectures)
- Optimistic concurrency control bypass
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify state-changing operations with multiple steps or checks
2. Map transaction boundaries and isolation levels
3. Test with increasing concurrency levels (N=2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100)
4. Use specialized synchronization techniques (HTTP/2, last-byte sync, connection warming)
5. Validate durable state changes (database, ledger, audit logs)
6. Test across different interfaces (REST, GraphQL, WebSocket, gRPC)
</methodology>

<toctou_exploits>
<concept>
{% raw %}
# Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU)
# Window between validation and action

# Classic pattern:
# 1. Check: if user.balance >= amount
# 2. Use: user.balance -= amount
#
# Race window: Between check and use
# Attack: Multiple concurrent requests pass check before any uses
{% endraw %}
</concept>

<balance_checks>
{% raw %}
# Balance/quota validation without atomic operations

# Single request (denied)
POST /api/transfer
{"amount": 1000, "to": "attacker"}
# Response: Insufficient balance (balance: 100)

# Concurrent requests (may succeed)
# Send 10 parallel requests with amount=100
# If check is before deduction, all may pass validation
# Result: overdraft of 900

# Test script:
for i in {1..10}; do
  curl -X POST https://api.example.com/transfer \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
    -d '{"amount": 100, "to": "attacker"}' &
done
wait
{% endraw %}
</balance_checks>

<file_existence_checks>
{% raw %}
# File or resource existence checks

# Pattern:
# 1. Check: if not exists("file.txt")
# 2. Create: write("file.txt", content)

# Race: Two processes both pass check, both create file
# Result: One creation overwrites the other

# Or with unique constraints:
# 1. Check: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'test@example.com'
# 2. Insert: INSERT INTO users (email) VALUES ('test@example.com')
#
# Race: Both pass check, both attempt insert
# Result: Duplicate key error (if unique constraint) or duplicate records
{% endraw %}
</file_existence_checks>

