<limit_overrun_attacks>
<rate_limit_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Rate limits implemented with non-atomic counters

# Typical implementation:
# 1. Get current count
# 2. If count < limit, proceed
# 3. Increment count
#
# Race window: Between get and increment

# Attack: Send N requests simultaneously
# All may read same (low) count
# All proceed, then all increment
# Result: N requests processed instead of limit

# HTTP/2 technique for tight synchronization:
# Open HTTP/2 connection
# Send multiple requests on same connection
# They arrive nearly simultaneously

# Tool: Turbo Intruder (Burp Suite extension)
# Tool: http2-rapid-fire (custom script)
{% endraw %}
</rate_limit_bypass>

<quota_exhaustion>
{% raw %}
# API quotas, download limits, seat counts

# Single request (denied):
GET /api/download/large-file
# Response: Quota exceeded (used: 10GB, limit: 10GB)

# Concurrent approach:
# 1. Reset to just under limit
# 2. Send multiple download requests simultaneously
# 3. Each checks quota, all pass
# 4. All downloads proceed
# Result: quota overrun

# Similar for:
# - API call limits
# - Storage quotas
# - Concurrent user limits
# - Request per second (RPS) limits
{% endraw %}
</quota_exhaustion>

